The family 

Cirolanidae 
Dana, 1852

is one of the largest families of marine isopod, with forty-eight marine genera and 443 species accepted worldwide (

onwards). The Andaman Islands, while politically part of 
India
, is geographically situated in the eastern part of the Bay of Bengal and is therefore biogeographically part of western South-East Asia. Historically, the cirolanid fauna of South-East Asia, has received little attention since the 1900s with just occasional publications (

; 

, 

; 

; 

). More recently there has been sustained effort in documenting cirolanids from this region by Rodcharaoen and colleagues (

, 

, 

; 

) and by Sidabalok and Bruce (

; 

, 

, 

, 

, b) and there are now twelve genera of 
Cirolanidae
housing 45 species known from this region.

The family Cirolanidae in India is represented by 28 species in 10 genera (
). Only three reported species belong
Cirolana
, namely
Cirolana bovina Barnard, 1940
from Kerala (
);
Cirolana sulcaticauda Stebbing, 1904
from Gulf of Kutch (
);
Cirolana willeyi Stebbing, 1904
from Chilika lagoon and Kerala (
;
); a further two species have been shown to be misidentifications or doubtful (see below) leaving just three accepted species. In comparable regions the diversity of
Cirolana
is far higher with, for example, nine species from Thailand (Rodcharoen references) and 19 species from Indonesia and Singapore (Sidabalok references). Clearly the genus
Cirolana
, and equally the Cirolanidae , is massively under reported from Indian waters.

The 
Andaman and Nicobar Islands
lie in the tropical zone between the Bay of Bengal and northeastern Indian Ocean. Due to its remoteness, there has been a lack of research on marine crustaceans in general and knowledge still remains minimal in the region. The non-decapod taxa have received relatively little attention with just a few accounts of the Amphipoda (Sathyam 
et al.
2017) and 
Isopoda
